Content.Question: If this is an index of what is going on in Ohio, look out for a landslide here on the 6th of November, for we are all going one way. --, 1856

Content.Question: His first great speech..was a perfect land-slide of history of argument; an avalanche under which the opposing party were logically buried. --H. B. Stowe, 1868
Content.SuperMemoReference: <H5 dir=ltr align=left><Font size="1" style="color: transparent"> SuperMemo Reference:</font><br><FONT class=reference>Title:"My Test Quote" <br>Source: Oxford English Dictionary

SuperMemoElement.Title: An overwhelming majority of votes for one party or candidate in an election; a victory achieved with such a majority.

Content.Question: An overwhelming majority of votes for one party or candidate in an election; a victory achieved with such a majority. --This sense was first used in the year 1856, This usage is NOT obsolete., This sense is NOT the main sense for this word., landslide, n., sense 2
